ей Передней Азии, Кавказу и отчасти Европе; ср. <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/> <w>araqi</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sva"><lang/> <w>haraq</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lbe"><lang/> <w>araq</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="av"><lang/> <w>ʽaraqi</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="inh"><lang/> <w>qharaqh</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="bbl"><lang/> <w>araq</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/> <w>araqa, arqa</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="krc-x-balkar"><lang/> <w>araqə</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/> <w>арак, арака</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/> <w>Arrak</w></mentioned> и др.<note n="1"> PUT NOTE HERE
        </note></etym><etym xml:lang="en">From <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/> <w>ʽaraq</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><lang/> <w>araq, araqi</w><note type="comment" xml:lang="ru"> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Радлов"/><biblScope>I 250</biblScope></bibl>)</note><note type="comment" xml:lang="en"> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Радлов"/><biblScope>I 250</biblScope></bibl>)</note> <gloss><q>vodka</q></gloss></mentioned>; the word is spread throughout Western Asia, the Caucasus and partly Europe; cf. <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/> <w>araqi</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sva"><lang/> <w>haraq</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lbe"><lang/> <w>araq</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="av"><lang/> <w>ʽaraqi</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="inh"><lang/> <w>qharaqh</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="bbl"><lang/> <w>araq</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/> <w>araqa, arqa</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="krc-x-balkar"><lang/> <w>araqə</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/> <w>арак, арака</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/> <w>Arrak</w></mentioned> etc.<note n="1"> PUT NOTE HERE
        </note></etym><note type="footnote" xml:lang="ru" n="1">Первоисточником считают обычно <mentioned xml:lang="ar"><lang/> <w>ʽaraq</w> <gloss><q>пот</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Lokotsch"/><biblScope>9</biblScope></bibl>). Но %sRamstedt%s (<bibl><biblScope xml:lang="ru">Studies in Korean etymology. 1949, стр. 13</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">Studies in Korean etymology. 1949, p. 13</biblScope></bibl>), привлекая корейское <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/> <w>araq</w> <gloss><q>спиртной напиток</q></gloss></mentioned>, манджурское <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/> <w>arki</w></mentioned>, айну <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/> <w>arakke</w></mentioned>, японское <mentioned xml:lang="ja"><lang/> <w>sake</w></mentioned>, говорит о „древнем культурном слове“ и в этой связи приводит также, без указания источника, <mentioned xml:lang="hit"><lang/> <w>raki</w> <gloss><q>спиртной напиток</q></gloss></mentioned> (однако слова с начальным %ir-%i не свойственны хеттскому).</note><note type="footnote" xml:lang="en" n="1">The primary source is usually considered to be <mentioned xml:lang="ar"><lang/> <w>ʽaraq</w> <gloss><q>sweat</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Lokotsch"/><biblScope>9</biblScope></bibl>). But %sRamstedt%s (<bibl><biblScope xml:lang="ru">Studies in Korean etymology. 1949, стр. 13</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">Studies in Korean etymology. 1949, p. 13</biblScope></bibl>), drawing Korean <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/> <w>araq</w> <gloss><q>alcoholic beverage</q></gloss></mentioned>, Manchu <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/> <w>arki</w></mentioned>, Ainu <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/> <w>arakke</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ja"><lang/> <w>sake</w></mentioned>, speaks of an “ancient cultural word” and in this connection also cites, without specifying the source, <mentioned xml:lang="hit"><lang/> <w>raki</w> <gloss><q>спиртной напиток</q></gloss></mentioned> (however, words with initial %ir-%i are not typical for Hittite).</note></entry></body></text></TEI>